<article>

  <p>
    The Buddha's first teaching does not open with cosmology, consciousness, or the
    fate of the self after death. It opens with a problem most people already know
    from the inside:
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span> —
    the friction in conditioned experience that no amount of rearranging the furniture
    quite removes.
  </p>

  <p>
    A meal goes from anticipation to too much. Sun on the skin becomes heat; shade
    becomes chill. Wanting and not-wanting trade places all afternoon. The
    Dhammacakkappavattana
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sutta" data-en="discourse">Sutta</span>
    (SN 56.11) does not invent that oscillation. It names it, traces its cause, and
    says there is a way out that can be verified — not as a belief adopted from
    outside, but as a relationship to experience that can be trained.
  </p>

  <p>
    The title means something like "the discourse that sets the wheel of the
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dhamma" data-en="teaching">Dhamma</span>
    in motion." What follows is an attempt to read it carefully: what it claims, what
    it does not claim, and why the tradition treats this short text as the frame for
    almost everything else.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Who He Went to Find</h2>

  <p>
    The scene is Isipatana — the Deer Park near Benares — shortly after the awakening
    under the Bodhi tree. The Buddha walks there to find five
    <span class="pali" data-pali="bhikkhu" data-en="ones on the path">bhikkhus</span>
    who had practiced with him during the years of severe austerity. They left when he
    abandoned fasting and self-mortification. They thought he had fallen away. He comes
    back as someone who has found something they have not.
  </p>

  <p>
    The texts say his first impulse was not to teach. The
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dhamma" data-en="teaching">Dhamma</span>
    seemed too subtle, too easily misunderstood. Tradition recounts a turning — an
    entreaty, a decision — and then the walk to the five. Worth holding lightly as
    narrative detail; what matters for reading is the choice of audience and opening.
    He does not begin with people who need convincing that life has problems. He begins
    with people who already left everything to solve them — and still got the method wrong.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Not Moderation</h2>

  <p>
    Before the four truths, there is a practical cut. Two extremes, the Buddha tells
    the five, are not for someone who has left the household life: devotion to sensual
    pleasure — low, vulgar, unprofitable — and devotion to self-mortification — painful,
    ignoble, equally unprofitable. Both are to be abandoned.
  </p>

  <p>
    Between them is the
    <span class="pali" data-pali="majjhimā-paṭipadā" data-en="middle way">majjhimā paṭipadā</span>
    — the middle way. It gives rise to vision and knowledge, and leads to calm, to
    direct knowing, to awakening, to
    <span class="pali" data-pali="nibbāna" data-en="liberation">nibbāna</span>.
    That way is the
    <a href="/concepts/eightfold-path/">Noble Eightfold Path</a>:
    right view, right intention, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right
    effort, right mindfulness, right unification.
  </p>

  <p>
    The middle way is often read as a counsel of moderation — not too much pleasure,
    not too little food. That reading is not entirely wrong. It is too thin. The point
    is not a lifestyle compromise. Sensual indulgence treats pleasure as if it were
    solid and lasting. Mortification treats the body as an enemy to be defeated. Both
    are wrong relationships to experience. The path is the one that sees clearly enough
    to stop fighting experience with the wrong weapons.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Four Truths, Not a Creed</h2>

  <p>
    The core of the discourse is the four noble truths — announced in the careful
    language of a physician naming a condition, its cause, its ending, and its cure.
    They are not four slogans to recite. They are four tasks.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>The first truth.</strong>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">Dukkha</span>
    is to be fully understood. Birth, aging, illness, and death are
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>;
    so are association with what one dislikes, separation from what one loves, and
    not getting what one wants. In brief: the five aggregates subject to
    <span class="pali" data-pali="upadāna" data-en="clinging">upadāna</span>
    — clinging — are
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is not the claim that life is uniformly miserable. Pleasant experience is real.
    So is the way pleasant experience fails to stay. The teaching names a pervasive
    unsatisfactoriness in conditioned things — including the subtle friction of change —
    without denying joy. Pessimism is a misreading. Diagnosis is not.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>The second truth.</strong>
    The origin of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>
    is
    <span class="pali" data-pali="tanhā" data-en="craving">tanhā</span>
    — craving that leads to renewed existence, accompanied by delight and passion,
    seeking delight here and there: craving for sensual pleasure, craving for existence,
    craving for extermination. The problem is not that objects exist. The problem is
    the thirst that keeps leaning toward and away from them.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>The third truth.</strong>
    The cessation of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>
    is the remainderless fading and cessation of that same craving — its abandonment
    and relinquishment. This is
    <span class="pali" data-pali="nibbāna" data-en="liberation">nibbāna</span>:
    not the annihilation of a person, but the extinguishing of the fire that drives
    continued becoming. What goes out is the fuel. The texts are deliberately careful
    about what remains when the fuel is gone.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>The fourth truth.</strong>
    The path leading to that cessation is the
    <a href="/concepts/eightfold-path/">Noble Eightfold Path</a>.
    The prescription follows from the diagnosis. No separate metaphysics is required
    to begin.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    "This is the noble truth of suffering… This noble truth of suffering is to be fully
    understood… This noble truth of suffering has been fully understood."
    <cite>— SN 56.11 (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    What is striking is the starting point. He does not begin with a system to be
    assembled from the outside. He begins with what a listener can already recognise:
    that conditioned experience does not stay settled. The teaching orients toward a
    problem that is present — not a worldview that must be installed first.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Three Turnings of Each Truth</h2>

  <p>
    The sutta has a feature easy to skim past and costly to miss. For each truth the
    Buddha describes three "turnings" of the wheel: the statement of the truth; what
    must be done with respect to it; and the confirmation that it has been done.
  </p>

  <p>
    For
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>:
    <em>this is dukkha</em> — <em>dukkha is to be fully understood</em> —
    <em>dukkha has been fully understood</em>. For the origin: this is the origin; it
    is to be abandoned; it has been abandoned. For cessation: this is cessation; it is
    to be realised; it has been realised. For the path: this is the path; it is to be
    developed; it has been developed.
  </p>

  <p>
    The structure makes the teaching empirical rather than merely doctrinal. These are
    not propositions parked in the intellect. They describe a relationship between
    attention and experience that can be tested. The third turning — the confirmation —
    is not something the first-time listener can honestly say. It is what the Buddha
    reports from the far side of the work. It functions as both credential and promise:
    this can be known directly, because it has been.
  </p>

  <p>
    Of course a report is not yet one's own seeing. The sutta does not collapse that
    gap. It names it.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Kondañña Sees</h2>

  <p>
    At the end of the discourse, one of the five — Kondañña — attains the first stage
    of awakening. The text records that there arose in him the dustless, stainless
    vision of the
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dhamma" data-en="teaching">Dhamma</span>:
    "Whatever is subject to origination is all subject to cessation."
  </p>

  <p>
    The seeing is precise. Not "everything is impermanent" as a vague mood, but the
    specific recognition that anything arisen through conditions will cease when those
    conditions cease. That is the hinge. If craving is a condition, and craving can
    cease, then the suffering that depends on it is not a permanent feature of being
    alive. Kondañña has understood the hinge on which liberation turns.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Buddha responds:
    <em>"Kondañña has understood! Kondañña has understood!"</em>
    — and from this he receives the name Aññāsi Kondañña: Kondañña-who-has-known.
    The wheel is no longer only what one person has seen alone. It is something that
    can be transmitted, practiced, and confirmed.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>How to Hold This</h2>

  <p>
    In a sense, the Dhammacakkappavattana Sutta is the frame within which the other
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sutta" data-en="discourse">suttas</span>
    operate. The four truths are the diagnostic structure the tradition returns to
    again and again. Reading it carefully means noticing what it does not say as much
    as what it does.
  </p>

  <p>
    It does not say that life is a mistake. It does not settle the metaphysics of self
    and afterlife in this first talk — those questions arrive later, and often by
    refusal rather than theory. It says there is
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>,
    that it has a cause that can be understood, that cessation is possible, and that
    there is a trainable path. Notes, not a closed system.
  </p>

  <p>
    The question it puts to a reader is not "Do you accept these four propositions?"
    It is closer to: are you willing to look at wanting and not-wanting honestly enough
    to see whether the diagnosis holds? The rest of the canon elaborates. This text
    turns the wheel.
  </p>

</article>
